solutions.Solution 2:
It is fairly natural to use Lagrange's Interpolation Formula on this problem:


\begin{align*} P(n+1) &= \sum_{k=0}^n \frac{k}{k+1} \prod_{j \ne k} \frac{n+1-j}{k-j} \\ &= \sum_{k=0}^n \frac{k}{k+1} \cdot \frac{\frac{(n+1)!}{n+1-k}}{k(k-1)(k-2) \dots 1\cdot (-1)(-2) \dots (k-n)} \\ &= \sum_{k=0}^n \frac{k}{k+1} (-1)^{n-k}\cdot \frac{(n+1)!}{k!(n+1-k)!} \\ &= \sum_{k=0}^n (-1)^{n-k} \binom{n+1}{k} - \sum_{k=0}^n \frac{(n+1)!(-1)^{n-k}}{(k+1)!(n+1-k)!} \\ &= -\left(\sum_{k=0}^{n+1} (-1)^{n+1-k} \binom{n+1}{k} - 1\right) + \frac{1}{n+2} \cdot \sum_{k=0}^n (-1)^{n+1-k} \binom{n+2}{k+1} \\ &= 1 + \frac{1}{n+2} \left(\sum_{k=-1}^{n+1} (-1)^{n+2 - (k+1)} \binom{n+2}{k+1} - (-1)^{n+2} - 1\right) \\ &= \boxed{1 - \frac{(-1)^n + 1}{n+2}} \end{align*}
through usage of the Binomial Theorem. $\square$


